dc.description: Two story wooden building next to a post office and general store in an unnamed town. A small crowd of people stands on the porch of the building. According to the 1907 "The Book of Minnesotans: A Biographical Dictionary of Leading Living Men of the State of Minnesota," John P. Hedberg was born in Sweden on May 3, 1853 and came to America in 1869. He opened a lumber business in 1882 in Brandon, Minnesota under the title of of "J. P. Hedberg & Co." and in 1887 moved to Kensington where he engaged in "lumber, hardware and furniture business."

description: A letter from a O. D. Storrs, in Winsted Lake, Minnesota, to an administrator at the Protestant Orphan Asylum. The woman has taken an orphaned boy, Charley, on a "trial" basis and explains in her letter that she has decided to adopt him permanently.

April 12th, [18]75 
Winsted Lake, Minn 
Mrs. Thompson 
St. Paul 
Minnesota 
You can send the papers 
to be filled out at any time. 
Little Charley is well 
& happy as a lark.  He has had 
the whooping cough, but is 
nearly well of it now[.] 
He is a milder dispositioned 
child that I imagined at 
first.  We love him very 
much, & will give him the 
same advantages that we 
would if he were our own[.] 
He calls us Pa & Ma, & has 
a good time with his little 
baby sister[.] 
Yours truly 
O. D. Storrs
subject: Letters; Orphans; Orphanages
Orphanage; Adoption; Social welfare
dc.publisher: Amherst H. Wilder Foundation, 451 Lexington Parkway North, St. Paul, MN 55104 www.wilder.org

dc.title: Chief Bemidji and his family, Bemidji, Minnesota
dc.description: Chief Bemidji, whose real name was " Shay-Now-Ish -Kung," received his new name from Lake Bemidji which was called Bay-me-ji-ga, or "lake with cross waters." He was born near Inger, Minnesota, in 1833 or 1834 and lived in the Leech Lake and Cass Lake area. In 1860, he married a Leech Lake Pillager Indian woman and they had eight children, three boys of whom died at early ages. Four daughters and one son grew up and lived to older ages. In 1882, Chief Bemidji's wife died. Saddened by her death, he loaded all his possessions and children in his birch bark canoe and paddled up the Mississippi River to settle on the south shore of Lake Bemidji. He was the first permanent settler of Bemidji (from p. 107,"The Bemidji Area Looking Back" 2004).
